    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1426589018" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1426589018" />
    <a title="Beth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6074441-beth"><img alt="Beth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1352692366p2/6074441.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1426589018?book_show_action=true">Oct 27, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beth" href="/user/show/6074441-beth">Beth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6074441-beth?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6074441-beth?shelf=1970s-sff-by-women">1970s-sff-by-women</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6074441-beth?shelf=fantasy-by-women">fantasy-by-women</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1426589018" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8206081753984654309">I&apos;ve had this book forever, but had never actually read it, and it ended up being a short book for a busy month, as well as fitting in with several of my reading projects: (1) YA (2) books owned but unread for literally decades (3) older SF and fantasy by women (before 2000 or so). This one is from 1978.<br/><br/>I will start by apologizing to anyone who loved this book as a kid and who remains fond of it today....<br/> <br/>I&apos;m sorry. <br/><br/>Well, let&apos;s press on.<br/><br/>Life in Half-Circle Hold on Pern is dour and humorless, Pur</span>
  <span id="freeText8206081753984654309" style="display:none">I've had this book forever, but had never actually read it, and it ended up being a short book for a busy month, as well as fitting in with several of my reading projects: (1) YA (2) books owned but unread for literally decades (3) older SF and fantasy by women (before 2000 or so). This one is from 1978.<br /><br />I will start by apologizing to anyone who loved this book as a kid and who remains fond of it today....<br /> <br />I'm sorry. <br /><br />Well, let's press on.<br /><br />Life in Half-Circle Hold on Pern is dour and humorless, Puritanical in feel without any convincing justification for it in the text. There's no laughter in the face of trouble, here--Thread is serious business. The sole concession to amusement in a life otherwise 100% devoted to communal labor is the Harper, and he (always he, of course) only has a place at the Hold because he teaches the children history and the Pern code of conduct through a preapproved roster of songs. <br /><br />Fifteen-year-old Menolly's family has no affection for its youngest daughter; none of them has a kind word to say to or about her, and have nothing better to do with their spare time than to police her to make sure she isn't composing music, 'cause only dudes are allowed to do that. She has perfect pitch, and can play any instrument like a virtuoso with very little practice. But that isn't important.... Oh no, she hummed something non-canonical! Whip her with a belt! <br /><br />These jerks all but dance with glee when Menolly injures her hand so badly she nearly loses it, leaving her "crippled"--oh, you, '70s!--and unable to play musical instruments. (And we later find her mother may have <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[deliberately sabotaged her hand's healing so she wouldn't be able to play <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. What a bunch of assholes.) Later, when Menolly runs away from the hold, they don't worry or grieve, even though she could be dead to a recent incursion of Thread. They shrug and say she didn't toe the line, so it's her own stupid fault. <br /><br />Thank goodness, after running away, Menolly finds affection and understanding in a newly-hatched nest of small dragon-like creatures called fire lizards. She Impresses (with a capital "I" because Important World-Building Concepts are Capitalized in this World) all nine of the lizards who live through the hatching, and spends many happy days singing to and feeding them.<br /><br />Menolly finds her way to one of the dragon Weyrs when a dragonrider rescues her from another Thread attack. The Weyr is full of overbearing and snippy people, but at least they don't treat her like poo on their shoes, and they're open-minded about scandalous things like women performing art. They even offer to let her stay there forever.<br /><br />As sarcastic as I am about <i>Dragonsong</i> here, this was enjoyable to read. Not so much in the first half, since I found the presentation of the Half-Circle Hold folk ham-handed and unconvincing. I felt an affinity for the Benden Weyr people, though, or at least their easygoing culture, which, similar to the general vibe of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6320099-crystal-singer" rel="nofollow noopener">Crystal Singer</a> which I read a year or two ago, has a lot of congenial hanging out in between the hard work (not to mention copious amounts of alcohol). Reminds me of my own young adulthood right after college, actually.<br /><br />I couldn't really tell the Benden Weyr people apart, with T'This and T'That and T'Other, and Semolina and Purina and Bologna (I'm making these up, of course, but the men's and women's names follow this general pattern), and I'm guessing that if you've read the earlier books in the Pern series, you'll recognize familiar characters in Weyr Benden.<br /><br />There's a convincing sense of ecology to Pern, and of a society where the smaller settlements have had to revert to hunting and gathering, since staying in the open can be deadly to people, domesticated animals, and crops. Menolly can use outdoors skills to feed both herself and her fire lizard friends when she runs away, but on the downside is lacking in means to make her own shoes and clothing. So that was a cool detail. Also, the areas around Half-Circle Hold, and Benden Weyr itself, had a real sense of place for me. Although, as someone steeped in the U.S.'s car culture, I wonder how large of an area the map in the front of the book actually covers. At times, I thought you could easily walk from one settlement to another in a day, which made me confused when the dragons needed to teleport between settlements rather than just flying.<br /><br />There are ways in which <i>Dragonsong</i> feels old; it's younger than I am, and <i>I'm</i> not old, so I'm not sure what's going on, there. (Heh, heh.) Menolly doesn't seem as beholden to men as <i>Crystal Singer</i>'s Killashandra did, and there's Lessa at Benden Weyr to mitigate the idea that it's only men who are ever in charge on Pern, so I think it's McCaffrey's writing style, heavy in adverbs*, that gives it that old-school feeling. Or the unabashed use of storytelling elements--such as psychic bonds with hyper-intelligent animals--that may have been stylish at the time, but are embarrassing to wear in public today. It isn't McCaffrey's fault I read this almost 40 years after it came out.<br /><br />*I'm not entirely on board with the current notion that prose pruned of all adverbs and adjectives is superior, but here things have gone too far in the other direction.<br /><br />I'm kind of sorry that I ignored <i>Dragonsong</i>, or even found it boring, when I was of an age to appreciate it, since my cynicism makes me unable to connect with ultra-talented Menolly and her adorable little pets who somehow understand human speech and gestures from birth. Or the idea that the world might fall all over itself to take care of one lone girl in her time of need and give her a kind home and the recognition she deserves.<br /><br />Despite everything, McCaffrey kept me turning the pages and I'm interested in reading more about Pern. It isn't hard to see why she was a bestseller in her day. She was a fine storyteller.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8206081753984654309" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


